) identifying files to delete during rewind. The change is **low-risk overall** given this is a local CLI tool running inside user-owned git repos. However, there is one finding worth addressing (filenames containing newlines) and several informational observations.\n\n**Overall Risk Rating: Low**\n\n---\n\n## Detailed Findings\n\n### Finding 1: Filenames Containing Newlines -- Incorrect Parsing (Medium)\n\n**File:** `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/common.go`, lines 1246-1253\n\n**Description:**\nThe `gitUntrackedFiles()` function splits git output on `\\n`:\n\n```go\nfor _, f := range strings.Split(raw, \"\\n\") {\n    if f != \"\" && !isProtectedPath(f) {\n        files = append(files, f)\n    }\n}\n```\n\nGit filenames can legally contain newline characters. When this happens, `git ls-files` without the `-z` flag will quote such filenames (wrapping them in double quotes and escaping special characters), or the newlines will cause one filename to be split into multiple entries. This leads to incorrect file paths being returned -- phantom entries that do not correspond to real files, or split entries that fail to match any actual file.\n\nNotably, the same codebase already handles this correctly in `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/checkpoint/temporary.go` at line 1078, where `git status --porcelain -z` is used with NUL-separated output:\n\n```go\n// Use -z for NUL-separated output (handles quoted filenames with spaces/special chars)\ncmd := exec.CommandContext(ctx, \"git\", \"status\", \"--porcelain\", \"-z\", \"-uall\")\n```\n\n**Impact:**\n- A filename containing a literal newline (e.g., created by `touch $'file\\nname'`) would be parsed as two separate entries, neither matching a real file.\n- In the rewind context (`manual_commit_rewind.go` line 355), `filepath.Join(repoRoot, relPath)` would construct an incorrect path. The `os.Remove()` call would fail silently (file not found), so no unintended deletion occurs. However, the real file would not be deleted when it should be.\n- In the `collectUntrackedFiles` context, the split filename would be stored in `UntrackedFilesAtStart`, causing incorrect preservation decisions during rewind.\n\n**Exploitability:** Very low. Requires a user (or agent) to intentionally create a file with a newline in its name. Git discourages this. In practice, nearly no one does this.\n\n**Recommendation:**\nUse the `-z` flag to get NUL-separated output, matching the pattern already used in `checkpoint/temporary.go`:\n\n```go\ncmd := exec.CommandContext(context.Background(), \"git\", \"ls-files\", \"--others\", \"--exclude-standard\", \"-z\")\ncmd.Dir = repoRoot\noutput, err := cmd.Output()\nif err != nil {\n    return nil, fmt.Errorf(\"git ls-files failed: %w\", err)\n}\n\nraw := string(output)\nif raw == \"\" {\n    return nil, nil\n}\n\nvar files []string\nfor _, f := range strings.Split(raw, \"\\x00\") {\n    if f != \"\" && !isProtectedPath(f) {\n        files = append(files, f)\n    }\n}\nreturn files, nil\n```\n\n---\n\n### Finding 2: No Command Injection Risk (Informational -- No Issue)\n\n**File:** `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/common.go`, line 1239\n\n```go\ncmd := exec.CommandContext(context.Background(), \"git\", \"ls-files\", \"--others\", \"--exclude-standard\")\n```\n\nThe `exec.CommandContext` call uses only hardcoded string arguments. No user input or variable is interpolated into the command or its arguments. The `cmd.Dir` is set to `repoRoot` which comes from `git rev-parse --show-toplevel`, not from user input. There is no command injection vector here.\n\n---\n\n### Finding 3: Path Traversal in `filepath.Join(repoRoot, relPath)` -- Mitigated (Low)\n\n**File:** `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/manual_commit_rewind.go`, line 355\n\n```go\nabsPath := filepath.Join(repoRoot, relPath)\nif removeErr := os.Remove(absPath); removeErr == nil {\n```\n\n**Description:**\nIf `relPath` from `git ls-files` output contained a path traversal component like `../../../etc/passwd`, the `filepath.Join` would resolve it to a path outside the repository, and `os.Remove` could delete an arbitrary file.\n\n**Mitigating Factors:**\n1. `git ls-files --others --exclude-standard` returns paths relative to the repository root. Git does not output paths containing `..` components in its `ls-files` output. The data source is the git index/working tree, not arbitrary user input.\n2. The `isProtectedPath` check at line 1253 in `common.go` filters `.git/` and `.entire/` paths, but does not check for `..` traversal. However, since the data source is git itself, `..` would never appear.\n3. The old `filepath.Walk` code had the same trust model -- it walked filesystem paths and deleted files found during traversal.\n\n**Recommendation:**\nAs a defense-in-depth measure, you could add a `..` check to `gitUntrackedFiles()`:\n\n```go\nif f != \"\" && !isProtectedPath(f) && !strings.Contains(f, \"..\") {\n    files = append(files, f)\n}\n```\n\nThis is optional given the low risk, but it would guard against any hypothetical git bug or edge case.\n\n---\n\n### Finding 4: `isProtectedPath` Check Is Sufficient After the Switch (Informational -- No Issue)\n\n**File:** `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/common.go`, line 1253\n\nThe `isProtectedPath` filter is applied inside `gitUntrackedFiles()` and prevents `.git/`, `.entire/`, and agent config directories from being returned. This protection is applied in the same way as the old `filepath.Walk` code.\n\nHowever, there is an important difference: the old `filepath.Walk` code used `filepath.SkipDir` to skip entire protected directory trees efficiently. The new code relies on `git ls-files --exclude-standard` which already excludes `.git/` (git never lists its own internals). The `.entire/` directory would appear in the output only if it is not gitignored. Looking at the `EnsureEntireGitignore` function (line 667), the `.entire/` directory gets its own `.gitignore` but the directory itself is not necessarily in the repo root `.gitignore`. So `.entire/` files that are not covered by `.entire/.gitignore` could potentially appear in the output -- but `isProtectedPath` correctly filters them.\n\n**Assessment:** The protection is sufficient. No issue.\n\n---\n\n### Finding 5: Git Binary Unavailability (Low)\n\n**File:** `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/common.go`, lines 1239-1243\n\n```go\ncmd := exec.CommandContext(context.Background(), \"git\", \"ls-files\", \"--others\", \"--exclude-standard\")\ncmd.Dir = repoRoot\noutput, err := cmd.Output()\nif err != nil {\n    return nil, fmt.Errorf(\"git ls-files failed: %w\", err)\n}\n```\n\n**Description:**\nIf the `git` binary is not available on PATH, `cmd.Output()` returns an error. This error propagates as:\n- In `collectUntrackedFiles()`: The error bubbles up. If this fails during session start, untracked files would not be captured, meaning those files could be deleted during a later rewind.\n- In `Rewind()` (line 333-337): The error is caught as non-fatal and logged to stderr. Rewind proceeds without deleting any untracked files, which is the safe default.\n\n**Assessment:** The error handling is appropriate. Rewind gracefully degrades. The only concern is that `collectUntrackedFiles()` failure at session start could lead to data loss during rewind (untracked files present at start not being preserved). However, this is the same behavior as the old code -- if `filepath.Walk` failed, the same issue would occur. And git being unavailable when running a git-integrated CLI tool is an extreme edge case.\n\n---\n\n### Finding 6: `.gitignore` Exclusion Could Skip Security-Relevant Files (Informational -- By Design)\n\n**Description:**\nThe old `filepath.Walk` code collected ALL untracked files (including gitignored ones). The new `git ls-files --others --exclude-standard` excludes files matched by `.gitignore`. This means:\n- Files in `node_modules/`, `build/`, or other gitignored directories are no longer collected in `UntrackedFilesAtStart`.\n- During rewind, these files are also not considered for deletion since `gitUntrackedFiles()` does not return them.\n\n**Security Implication:**\nThis is actually a security improvement. The old code would walk through massive directories like `node_modules/`, which is both slow and unnecessary. Gitignored files are not part of the git working state and should not be managed by the checkpoint system. The test `TestShadow_GitignoredFilesPreservedDuringRewind` explicitly validates that gitignored files survive rewind, and `TestShadow_GitignoredFilesExcludedFromSessionState` validates they are excluded from session state.\n\n**Assessment:** Correct behavior by design. No issue.\n\n---\n\n### Finding 7: No Timeout on `exec.CommandContext` (Low)\n\n**File:** `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/common.go`, line 1239\n\n```go\ncmd := exec.CommandContext(context.Background(), \"git\", \"ls-files\", \"--others\", \"--exclude-standard\")\n```\n\n`context.Background()` has no timeout. If `git ls-files` hangs (e.g., due to a network-mounted filesystem or corrupt git index), the CLI would hang indefinitely. The old `filepath.Walk` had the same issue (it could hang on a network mount).\n\n**Recommendation:** This is a low-priority, pre-existing pattern. The same `context.Background()` is used throughout the codebase (e.g., `GetWorktreePath`, `GetGitCommonDir`, `DeleteBranchCLI`). If you want to address it, a project-wide effort to add timeouts to git CLI calls would be appropriate, but this is not specific to this change.\n\n---\n\n## Risk Matrix\n\n| # | Finding | Severity | Exploitability | Action |\n|---|---------|----------|----------------|--------|\n| 1 | Newline-in-filename parsing | **Medium** | Very Low | Fix: use `-z` flag for NUL-separated output |\n| 2 | No command injection | Informational | N/A | No action needed |\n| 3 | Path traversal in `filepath.Join` | **Low** | Very Low | Optional defense-in-depth: reject `..` paths |\n| 4 | `isProtectedPath` sufficiency | Informational | N/A | No action needed |\n| 5 | Git binary unavailability | **Low** | Very Low | Already handled gracefully |\n| 6 | `.gitignore` exclusion behavior | Informational | N/A | By design, tested |\n| 7 | No timeout on exec | **Low** | Very Low | Pre-existing, not specific to this change |\n\n---\n\n## Remediation Roadmap\n\n**Priority 1 (Recommended before merge):**\n- **Finding 1**: Switch `gitUntrackedFiles()` to use `-z` for NUL-separated output. This is a small change that aligns with the existing pattern in `checkpoint/temporary.go` and eliminates the edge case completely.\n\n**Priority 2 (Nice to have):**\n- **Finding 3**: Add a `..` path component check in `gitUntrackedFiles()` as defense-in-depth.\n\n**No action required:**\n- Findings 2, 4, 5, 6, 7 are either informational or already handled correctly.\n\n---\n\n## Security Requirements Checklist (for this change)\n\n- [x] All inputs validated and sanitized -- git output is parsed and filtered through `isProtectedPath`\n- [x] No hardcoded secrets or credentials\n- [x] Proper authentication on all endpoints -- N/A (local CLI tool)\n- [x] SQL queries use parameterization -- N/A\n- [x] XSS protection implemented -- N/A\n- [x] HTTPS enforced where needed -- N/A\n- [x] CSRF protection enabled -- N/A\n- [x] Security headers properly configured -- N/A\n- [x] Error messages don't leak sensitive information -- errors show git command output only\n- [x] Dependencies are up-to-date -- no new dependencies added\n- [ ] **Partial**: Filenames with special characters (newlines) not fully handled -- recommend `-z` flag</result>\n<usage>total_tokens: 84302\ntool_uses: 14\nduration_ms: 99714</usage>\n</task-notification>\nFull transcript available at: /private/tmp/claude-501/-Users-soph-Work-entire-devenv-cli/tasks/a4ec7c5.output\n\n---\n\n<task-notification>\n<task-id>a9dfead</task-id>\n<tool-use-id>toolu_01FtcAqjAPWRVoXcMqCa3J1w</tool-use-id>\n<status>completed</status>\n<summary>Agent \"Performance review of changes\" completed</summary>\n<result>Good. I now have a comprehensive picture of the change. Let me assemble the full performance analysis.\n\n---\n\n## Performance Analysis: `filepath.Walk` to `git ls-files` Migration\n\n### 1. Performance Summary\n\nThis change replaces three separate `filepath.Walk` invocations (in `collectUntrackedFiles`, `Rewind`, and `PreviewRewind`) with calls to `git ls-files --others --exclude-standard`. The motivation is correct and the performance improvement is substantial for the target use case (repositories with large `.gitignore`-ed directories like `node_modules/`). The new integration tests (`TestShadow_GitignoredFilesExcludedFromSessionState` and `TestShadow_GitignoredFilesPreservedDuringRewind`) properly validate the behavioral change.\n\n### 2. Critical Issues\n\nNone found. The change is a clear improvement and the new behavior is actually more correct than the old one. The old `filepath.Walk` implementation did not respect `.gitignore` at all -- it walked every file in the repository, including `node_modules/`, `build/`, etc. The only directories it skipped were the hardcoded protected paths (`.git/`, `.entire/`, agent config dirs). This means:\n\n- **Old behavior**: `collectUntrackedFiles` returned ALL files (tracked + untracked + ignored), minus protected paths. Session state stored tens of thousands of ignored file paths for repos with `node_modules/`.\n- **New behavior**: Returns only untracked, non-ignored files. This is semantically correct for the purpose of \"files to preserve during rewind.\"\n\n### 3. Answering the Specific Performance Questions\n\n**Q1: Is spawning `git ls-files` cheaper than `filepath.Walk` for repos with large ignored dirs?**\n\nYes, dramatically. The analysis breaks down as follows:\n\n- `filepath.Walk` performs a `stat()` syscall for every file and directory it encounters. For a repo with 50,000 files in `node_modules/`, that is 50,000+ syscalls, each requiring a kernel context switch. The old code's only skip mechanism was `filepath.SkipDir` on `.git/` and `.entire/`, so it walked the entirety of `node_modules/`, `build/`, etc.\n\n- `git ls-files --others --exclude-standard` uses git's internal directory-entry cache. Git reads `.gitignore` rules, and when it encounters a directory that matches an ignore pattern (like `node_modules/`), it skips the entire directory tree without descending into it. This is equivalent to the `SkipDir` optimization but applied via `.gitignore` rules rather than hardcoded paths.\n\n- The process spawn overhead (fork + exec) is approximately 2-5ms on macOS. For a repository with 50,000 ignored files, the `filepath.Walk` approach takes hundreds of milliseconds to several seconds. The crossover point where process spawn becomes cheaper than walking is very low -- likely around 100-200 ignored files.\n\n- **Projected numbers**: For a typical JavaScript project with `node_modules/`:\n  - Old (`filepath.Walk`): 500ms-3s depending on disk cache state\n  - New (`git ls-files`): 5-20ms total (spawn + git index lookup + output parsing)\n  - Improvement: 25x-150x faster\n\n**Q2: What is the memory impact of reading all output into a single string before splitting?**\n\nThe current implementation at `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/common.go` lines 1239-1257:\n\n```go\noutput, err := cmd.Output()\n// ...\nraw := strings.TrimSpace(string(output))\n// ...\nfor _, f := range strings.Split(raw, \"\\n\") {\n```\n\nThis creates three copies of the data in memory simultaneously:\n1. `output` (the `[]byte` from `cmd.Output()`)\n2. `string(output)` (Go string conversion copies the bytes)\n3. The `[]string` slice from `strings.Split`\n\nFor a reasonable number of untracked, non-ignored files (the typical case), this is negligible. Even 10,000 untracked files with 50-byte average paths would be ~500KB per copy, so ~1.5MB peak. This is well within acceptable bounds for a CLI tool.\n\nHowever, the old `filepath.Walk` code had unbounded memory too (it appended every file path to a slice), so the new code is actually better because it processes a smaller set of files (only untracked non-ignored, vs. ALL non-protected files).\n\n**Optimization opportunity** (low priority): If memory became a concern, you could use `bufio.Scanner` on `cmd.StdoutPipe()` to process line-by-line without buffering the entire output. This is not necessary for the current use case.\n\n**Q3: Are there repos where `git ls-files` could be slower than Walk?**\n\nIn theory, yes, but not in practice for this use case:\n\n- A repository with zero `.gitignore` rules and millions of untracked files would make `git ls-files` enumerate the same files as `filepath.Walk`, plus the process spawn overhead. But even then, git's directory traversal is highly optimized (it uses the same `readdir` + `stat` pattern but with better directory-entry caching).\n\n- A repository with a corrupt or missing git index could cause `git ls-files` to fail entirely (returning an error), whereas `filepath.Walk` would still succeed. The code handles this correctly by returning an error from `gitUntrackedFiles`.\n\n- In the `Rewind` path (line 333-337 of `manual_commit_rewind.go`), the error is handled gracefully as non-fatal, which is the right approach.\n\n**Q4: Should `context.Background()` have a timeout?**\n\nYes. This is a moderate-priority improvement. The current code at line 1239:\n\n```go\ncmd := exec.CommandContext(context.Background(), \"git\", \"ls-files\", \"--others\", \"--exclude-standard\")\n```\n\nIf git hangs (e.g., due to a lock file from another git process, NFS stale handle, or a repository with pathological `.gitignore` patterns), this will block indefinitely. The same issue exists for `GetWorktreePath()` at line 657, `GetGitCommonDir()` at line 635, and other `exec.CommandContext(context.Background(), ...)` calls throughout the file, so this is a pre-existing pattern rather than a regression.\n\n**Recommendation**: Add a timeout, either by threading a context from the caller or by using a local timeout:\n\n```go\nctx, cancel := context.WithTimeout(context.Background(), 30*time.Second)\ndefer cancel()\ncmd := exec.CommandContext(ctx, \"git\", \"ls-files\", \"--others\", \"--exclude-standard\")\n```\n\nThis is consistent with the fact that `git ls-files` should complete in well under a second for any reasonable repository. A 30-second timeout protects against pathological cases without affecting normal operation.\n\n**Q5: Is there a Go-native alternative using go-git that avoids the process spawn but still respects `.gitignore`?**\n\ngo-git v5 does have `worktree.Status()` which returns untracked files, and there is a `gitignore` package (`github.com/go-git/go-git/v5/plumbing/format/gitignore`). However:\n\n1. **`worktree.Status()` is already used elsewhere** (in `checkCanRewind` at line 732, `checkCanRewindWithWarning` at line 798). It walks the filesystem internally, similar to `filepath.Walk`. It does respect `.gitignore` for marking files as untracked vs. ignored, but its implementation is known to be slow for large repositories because it compares every file against the git index.\n\n2. **go-git's `.gitignore` support is incomplete**. It does not support all `.gitignore` patterns (notably, it has had issues with negation patterns `!` and nested `.gitignore` files in subdirectories). Using `git ls-files` guarantees 100% compatibility with the user's actual git configuration.\n\n3. **go-git v5 has known bugs** with worktree operations (as documented in the CLAUDE.md -- checkout and reset deleting ignored directories). Using the git CLI for untracked file enumeration is consistent with the project's established pattern of preferring the CLI for operations where go-git has reliability issues.\n\n**Verdict**: Shelling out to `git ls-files` is the correct choice for this codebase. It is consistent with the existing pattern, avoids go-git bugs, and provides correct `.gitignore` handling.\n\n### 4. Optimization Opportunities\n\n**4a. Redundant `GetWorktreePath()` calls**\n\n`gitUntrackedFiles()` calls `GetWorktreePath()` (which spawns `git rev-parse --show-toplevel`). This function is then called from:\n- `collectUntrackedFiles()` -> called during session start\n- `Rewind()` -> which already calls `GetWorktreePath()` at line 325, then calls `gitUntrackedFiles()` at line 333\n- `PreviewRewind()` -> which called `GetWorktreePath()` in the old code but the new code removed it (good)\n\nIn `Rewind()`, there is a double invocation of `GetWorktreePath()`: once at line 325 and once inside `gitUntrackedFiles()` at line 1234. Each call spawns a subprocess. This could be eliminated by accepting `repoRoot` as a parameter to `gitUntrackedFiles()`.\n\n**Current cost**: ~4-10ms per redundant call (subprocess spawn).\n**Expected gain**: Eliminates one subprocess spawn per rewind operation.\n**Implementation complexity**: Low -- add a `repoRoot string` parameter.\n\n**4b. Stale comment on `protectedDirs`**\n\nAt `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/common.go` line 221:\n\n```go\n// The result is cached via sync.Once since it's called per-file during filepath.Walk.\n```\n\nThis comment references `filepath.Walk` which no longer exists in the codebase for the untracked-file paths. The `isProtectedPath` function is still called per-file (now per-line from `git ls-files` output), so the caching is still beneficial, but the comment should be updated.\n\n**4c. The `collectUntrackedFiles` wrapper is now unnecessary**\n\n```go\nfunc collectUntrackedFiles() ([]string, error) {\n    return gitUntrackedFiles()\n}\n```\n\nThis one-line wrapper at line 1227 adds indirection without value. All three call sites could call `gitUntrackedFiles()` directly. The `Rewind` and `PreviewRewind` methods already call `gitUntrackedFiles()` directly (not through the wrapper). Only `manual_commit_session.go:213` still uses `collectUntrackedFiles`.\n\n**Implementation complexity**: Trivial -- inline the call.\n\n### 5. Scalability Assessment\n\n**Data Volume Projections**:\n\n| Scenario | Old (filepath.Walk) | New (git ls-files) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Small repo (100 files, no node_modules) | ~5ms | ~8ms (slightly slower due to process spawn) |\n| Medium repo (5K tracked, 50K ignored) | ~500ms | ~15ms |\n| Large repo (20K tracked, 200K ignored) | ~2-5s | ~25ms |\n| Monorepo (100K tracked, 500K ignored) | ~10-30s | ~50ms |\n\nThe new approach scales with the number of **untracked non-ignored files**, not the total number of files on disk. This is the correct scaling behavior for a tool that operates on working directory state.\n\n**Concurrent Usage**: Both `Rewind` and `PreviewRewind` spawn `git ls-files` as a subprocess. If multiple sessions run concurrently (which the design supports), multiple `git ls-files` processes could run simultaneously. This is safe because `git ls-files` only reads the index and filesystem -- it does not acquire any locks.\n\n**Behavioral Change to Validate**: The old `filepath.Walk` in `Rewind` walked ALL files (tracked, untracked, and ignored) and deleted untracked files not in the checkpoint. The new code only enumerates untracked non-ignored files via `git ls-files --others --exclude-standard`. This means:\n\n- **Ignored files created by the agent after a checkpoint will NOT be deleted during rewind.** For example, if an agent creates files in a `build/` directory that is `.gitignore`-ed, those files will persist after rewind. This is actually the correct behavior (users do not want their build caches, `node_modules/`, or log files destroyed during rewind), and it is validated by `TestShadow_GitignoredFilesPreservedDuringRewind`.\n\n### 6. Recommended Actions (Prioritized)\n\n1. **(Low effort, correctness)** Update the stale `filepath.Walk` comment on `protectedDirs()` at `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/common.go` line 221.\n\n2. **(Low effort, cleanup)** Consider inlining `collectUntrackedFiles()` since it is now a trivial wrapper around `gitUntrackedFiles()`. Alternatively, remove the wrapper and rename `gitUntrackedFiles` to `collectUntrackedFiles` to preserve the existing call site.\n\n3. **(Low effort, performance)** Eliminate the redundant `GetWorktreePath()` call in `Rewind()` by passing `repoRoot` as a parameter to `gitUntrackedFiles()`, or by caching the result.\n\n4. **(Medium effort, reliability)** Add a timeout to the `context.Background()` used in `gitUntrackedFiles()`. A 30-second timeout would protect against hangs without affecting normal operation. This is a pre-existing issue across the codebase, so it could be addressed as a separate follow-up.\n\n5. **(Low effort, test coverage)** Verify the integration tests pass with `mise run test:integration`, particularly the two new tests: `TestShadow_GitignoredFilesExcludedFromSessionState` and `TestShadow_GitignoredFilesPreservedDuringRewind`.\n\n### Overall Assessment\n\nThis is a well-motivated performance optimization that simultaneously improves correctness. The old `filepath.Walk` approach was O(N) where N = total files on disk (including ignored), while the new `git ls-files` approach is O(M) where M = untracked non-ignored files. For typical repositories, M << N by orders of magnitude. The change is safe, well-tested with two new integration tests, and consistent with the project's established pattern of using git CLI over go-git for reliability-sensitive operations.</result>\n<usage>total_tokens: 75485\ntool_uses: 10\nduration_ms: 104695</usage>\n</task-notification>\nFull transcript available at: /private/tmp/claude-501/-Users-soph-Work-entire-devenv-cli/tasks/a9dfead.output\n\n---\n\n<task-notification>\n<task-id>a886d8d</task-id>\n<tool-use-id>toolu_012ftPwouTrRB5YQ6iwGCnAr</tool-use-id>\n<status>completed